        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.| Railway Station | Orpington S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>March 19. 1876</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have been greatly interested and amused by your letter.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The longer I live the more I come to believe in inheritance. I have some “orderlings” in my own composition, and I wish that I had transmitted more of it to my own offspring. I daresay you know my friend F. Galton’s book on Hereditary Genius,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> &amp; I will let him read your letter as I am sure it will interest him</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10418.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. G. Fenwick, 17 March 1876</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1797.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Galton</ref> mentioned orderliness in his discussion of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1904.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Johann Wolfgang von Goethe</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2706.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Galton 1869</ref>, p. 233).</note>
        </div>        
            
